RT @FAHayek_Quotes: Perhaps the fact that we have seen millions voting themselves into complete dependence on a tyrant has made our generat‚Ä¶

The current trust system is completely falling apart as a result. Lots of interests and links with power and Governments are still keeping it alive and frequently financed with our taxes or via inflation.

Without bitcoin I have the feeling everything could be somehow glued together but with it, it seems like the final blow and it is just a matter of time many people will start wondering why should we keep some institutions the way they were if better alternatives show up.
It may mean the start of drammatic changes that I don't think anyone can truly anticipate

- Some people were publicly given authority, their opinion was trustworthy on any matter, if they happened to write in a particular newspaper, happened to work in a particular organization, awarded...
- Public organizations that were nearly untouchable are publicly ridiculized

With the advent of the internet 2 things are happening: 1st the spread of information allows us to understand that most of that trust was undeserved and 2nd new opinion leaders and Companies are slowly earning that trust by simply delivering actual results

- A Country provides its citizens the idea that its judiciary and police forces provide a proper level of security of its lives and private property
- Governments intervene in every single part of the Economy to let you believe that if you trust them, they can provide anything.

- Political parties used to mean the defense of a very particular set of ideas.
- Food authorities and even health recommendations have been nearly the word of God on what you should and should not do.
- The name of a currency used to mean trust in the issuer.

Trust is moving from those who say they provide results to those who actually do, what I call the largest trust transfer ever.

This is what keeps me awake at nights üëá
(inspired by @VictorErem )

- A newspaper was a brand that provided the reader trust that the information was reliable
- A University allowed an employer to trust an almost certain level of preparation in a potential employee
- A Bank rents fancy offices so that we believe they are solvent and solid
